<br>
Thank you all SO much for reminding me.<br>
<br>
We had a cat who liked to push out kittens and get pregnant again before we had a chance to give away the last litter.  We were going to have her fixed.<br>
<br>
This last litter, we sort of left her alone becuase she'd done well with the last two.<br>
<br>
And then we let the kittens out to play.  They were emaciated and listless.  We immediately took them all to the vet, who put them on a formula diet because mother cat wasn't making enough milk for them.  One tiny kitten we called Wee Mouse, because she was only slightly larger than an adult mouse;  Little gray thing, almost nothing.  Runt of the litter.  We were certain she wasn't long for this world.<br>
<br>
The other kittens responded to the therapy.  But not Wee Mouse.  I ended up feeding her gently by hand, knowing that eventually I would have to take her to the vet and have her put down.  It was so painfully frustrating to feed this little, live furry cute thing only to know I was going to be instrumental in its passing.  I couldn't help but cry.<br>
<br>
I took Wee Mouse and her sister, the other gray kitten, back to the vet for a comparison.  The other kitten was almost twice Mouse's size and looked healthier.  Mouse was sickly and didn't move much.  The other kitten walked around and fell off the examining table.<br>
<br>
The next day, that kitten was dead.  I don't know if momma cat smothered her, or she died of something else.  All I know is that I came to check on the babies and saw one kitten not moving.  She was warm and her tongue was out and still wet, but she was dead.  Her sightless eyes stared at me sadly.<br>
<br>
I have never felt so helpless in my life.<br>
<br>
Here was a kitten whom I hadn't even bothered to name yet because I figured we'd have 'em a few more weeks and let the new owners name them, and now she was gone.  It was as if I didn't love her enough and now she was taken from me.<br>
<br>
My wife found me, sitting on the back doorstep when she came home, with this little dead kitten in my hands, crying.<br>
<br>
Sometimes life is just like that.<br>
<br>
Wee Mouse is now all grown up.  A little small but she sleeps with me during the day, curled up against my hand.  Every time I look at her, I remember her sister, and hold her just a little closer and listen to her purr. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dalliancefv>DallianceFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>WTFeth!</span><br>  Posts: 290<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/4/03 3:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3771.topic&index=16>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Death and loss</span><hr size=1> Wow. <br>
<br>
I've had pets all of my life -- I've always been attracted to strays, I suppose, and can't help but try to be the one that saves them, the one that makes a difference to one soul. The fear of the death, however, unlike other fears, never kept me from loving them without reserve.<br>
<br>
The first death I ever witnessed, like Larraque, was that of a bird. He had fallen from a tree sometime during the late hours of the night or the grey hours of the morning, and I noticed him flinching as I made my way to the bus stop.  He was beautiful, a myriad of colors, the most prominent of which was a bright red, and I do regret that I never found out what kind of bird he was. I have yet to see another bird like him. I named him Sebastien because I've always loved that name. <br>
<br>
Having the soft, smushy heart that I do, I gently picked him up and laid him in a box to take to my biology teacher. Back in those days, science teachers were second only to neurosurgeons as objects of my hero-worship. She could save him, certainly.<br>
<br>
She couldn't.<br>
<br>
He did last through that day, and even that night. I had popped in to see him during my lunch period on the following day, and he looked much better. He had apparently broken his wing, and most likely suffered internal injuries but I could tell he wanted to fly again -- he was struggling with such determination that I smiled even as I had tears running down my face. <br>
<br>
He wasn't looking at me; his small face was turned toward the wall.  His tiny breast puffed out and he was gone. It was that fast. I was horrified. Had I blinked at that time, I would have missed it.  It was far from pleasant, but I am still glad that I was the one that was lucky enough to witness the passing of this incredible bird. <br>
<br>
I don't remember the rest of the day -- I might have even checked out early. I do know that I couldn't concentrate on anything but this beautiful, beautiful bird that I had been lucky enough to know, even if it was during a very brief and painful  time of his life. <br>
<br>
I had a cat later that was actually harder to take due to the length of time I had shared his company, but it was nothing like the shock I felt when Sebastien left.<br>
<br>
It was ironic that Sebastien, the bird, and Loki, the cat, would have been mortal enemies in life.  In death, however, they were brothers, and the world dimmed just a bit with their passings. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ifrinnofthebrood>Ifrinn of the brood</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 220<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/4/03 4:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3771.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Death and loss</span><hr size=1> <br>
